{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}} {{Use Indian English|date=April 2017}} '''Hathuwa Raj''' was a feudal estate belonging to [[Bhumihar]]s of Baghochia dynasty. It encompassed 1,365 villages, was inhabited by more than 391,000 people, and produced an annual rental of almost a million rupees.<ref>{{cite book | first = Anand A. | last = Yang | title = Bazaar India: Markets, Society, and the Colonial State in Bihar | publisher = [[University of California Press]] | year = 1999 | isbn = 978-0-520-21100-1 | pages = 305 (at page 69) }}</ref> It is located in the [[Saran Division]] of [[Bihar]].Earlier seats of the Raj included Huseypur, Kalyanpur, Balchowra and Baghoch. The Kalyanpur chieftaincy was subjugated by the Mughal Emperor Akbar during late 16th century. The ruling dynasty has a history of over 2000 years and one of the deepest genealogy in India.
Sir Kishen Pratap Sahi Bahadur who was Bhumihar and [[Maharaja]] between 1874 to 1896 was an ascetic. Soon after his coronation, he set out on a pilgrimage to the shrines of [[Northern India]]. Later on he used to regularly go on traveling and pilgrimage, mostly in [[Benares]].<ref>{{cite book | first = Anand A. | last = Yang | title = Bazaar India: Markets, Society, and the Colonial State in Bihar | publisher = [[University of California Press]] | year = 1999 | isbn = 978-0-520-21100-1 | pages = 305 (at page 140) }}</ref>
Due to its central location, Hathwa was the seat of the raja's residential palace and its nearby villages housed most of the key retainers of the estate.<ref>{{cite book | first = Anand A. | last = Yang | title = Bazaar India: Markets, Society, and the Colonial State in Bihar | publisher = [[University of California Press]] | year = 1999 | isbn = 978-0-520-21100-1 | pages = 305 (at page 193) }}</ref>
In addition to the estate ''Kachcheri'' (office), located in the Hathwa cluster of villages, were the estate manager's bungalow, the Diwan's house, the Hathwa Eden School, the post office, the Raj dispensary, the Durga medical hall and the temple called Gopal mandir.<ref>{{cite book | first = Anand A. | last = Yang | title = Bazaar India: Markets, Society, and the Colonial State in Bihar | publisher = [[University of California Press]] | year = 1999 | isbn = 978-0-520-21100-1 | pages = 305 (at page 194) }}</ref>
By the 1840s Hathwa was described as having large bazaars and bi-weekly markets. By the early nineteenth century, there were forts, palaces, and several temples constructed. An early twentieth-century account describes Hathwa as an impressive standard market, its shops offering a range of agricultural and consumer goods and its specialists providing a variety of services. The presence of schools and temples further accentuated its centrality in the locality. The estate collected ₹1400 annually as professional tax from traders stationed at Hathwa.<ref>{{cite book | first = Anand A. | last = Yang | title = Bazaar India: Markets, Society, and the Colonial State in Bihar | publisher = [[University of California Press]] | year = 1999 | isbn = 978-0-520-21100-1 | pages = 305 (at page 193) }}</ref>
==Durga Puja== Durga Puja was a major attraction for the Hathwa Raj family and all the family members would gather to worship their Durga at [[Thawe Mandir]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-10-22/patna/34652704_1_chief-priest-durga-puja-animal-sacrifice | title = Ex-zamindars' tryst with Durga Puja | author = Gayatree Sharma | publisher = [[The Times of India]] | date = 2012-10-22 | accessdate = 2012-10-22 }}</ref> Rituals consisted of the Maharaja traveling in a buggy to the Gopal Mandir, and then to the Sheesh Mahal for the annual durbar and onwards on an elephant for darshan of the Maiyya on Vijayadashmi.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/patna/Ex-zamindars-tryst-with-Durga-Puja/articleshow/16908429.cms | title = Ex-zamindars' tryst with Durga Puja | author = Gayatree Sharma | publisher = [[The Times of India]] | date = 2012-10-22 | accessdate = 2012-10-22 }}</ref> The Hathwa family still celebrates some of the customs including sacrificing buffaloes and goats during puja.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/patna/Ex-zamindars-tryst-with-Durga-Puja/articleshow/16908429.cms | title = Ex-zamindars' tryst with Durga Puja | author = Gayatree Sharma | publisher = [[The Times of India]] | date = 2015-03-10 | accessdate = 2012-10-22 }}</ref>
