[[Irreligion]] and [[atheism]] are present among a minority of mainly young people in [[Pakistan]].<ref>{{cite news|title= Pakistani youths turning into atheists |publisher= [[IBN Live]]|date=|url= http://ibnlive.in.com/news/pakistani-muslim-youths-turning-into-atheists/130354-19-93.html|accessdate=2012-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title= Global Index of Religiosity and Atheism |publisher= [[WIN/GIA|Gallup]]|date=|url= http://www.winmr.com/web/files/news/14/file/14.pdf |accessdate=2012-09-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title= The hardest part about being faithless|publisher= [[Pakistan Today]]|date=|url= http://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2014/02/08/comment/the-hardest-part-about-being-faithless/?|accessdate=2014-02-09}}</ref>
In 2005, about 1% of the population was estimated to be atheist, and by 2012, the figure rose to about 2% according to [[WIN/GIA|Gallup]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Husain |first=Irfan |title=Faith in decline |url=http://dawn.com/2012/08/27/faith-in-decline/ |accessdate=16 December 2012 |newspaper=Dawn |date=27 Aug 2012 |quote=Interestingly, and somewhat intriguingly, 2 per cent of the Pakistanis surveyed see themselves as atheists, up from 1pc in 2005. |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121204113125/http://dawn.com/2012/08/27/faith-in-decline/ |archivedate= 4 December 2012 |df= }}</ref>
Atheists in Pakistan face [[Discrimination against atheists|discrimination]], [[persecution]] and [[prejudice]] in society.<ref>{{cite news|title= What do Pakistani atheists mean for Pakistan?|publisher= [[The Express Tribune]]|date=|url= http://blogs.tribune.com.pk/story/8194/what-do-pakistani-atheists-mean-for-pakistan/|accessdate=2012-08-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title= Being Pakistani and atheist a dangerous combo, but some ready to brave it|publisher= [[Pakistan Today]]|date=|url= http://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2011/09/17/city/karachi/being-pakistani-and-atheist-a-dangerous-combo-but-some-ready-to-brave-it/|accessdate=2012-07-01}}</ref> Pakistan is reported by some sources to be among the seven countries where atheism can attract [[Capital punishment in Pakistan|capital punishment]], but according to the Library of Congress of the United States, '''"there is no specific statutory law that criminalizes apostasy in Pakistan."''<ref>{{cite news|last=Fisher|first=Max|title=The seven countries where the state can execute you for being atheist|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2012/12/10/the-seven-countries-where-the-state-can-execute-you-for-being-atheist/|accessdate=16 December 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=10 Dec 2012|quote=Though that list includes some dictatorships, the country that appears to most frequently condemn atheists to death for their beliefs is actually a democracy, if a frail one: Pakistan. Others include Saudi Arabia, Iran, Afghanistan, Sudan, the West African state of Mauritania, and the Maldives, an island nation in the Indian Ocean.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Laws Criminalizing Apostasy|url=https://www.loc.gov/law/help/apostasy/|website=Library of Congress|accessdate=28 May 2016}}</ref> On the other hand, the Pakistani government can impose the [[blasphemy law in Pakistan|death penalty for blasphemy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2013/12/13-countries-where-atheism-punishable-death/355961/}}</ref>
Internet groups such as ''Atheist and Agnostic Alliance Pakistan'' (AAAP) website have emerged which received over 17,000 hits within 48 hours of their launch.<ref>{{cite news|title= Pakistani Atheists and Agnostics take message online |publisher= [[The Express Tribune]]|date=|url= http://tribune.com.pk/story/261527/pakistani-athiests-and-agnostics-take-message-online/|accessdate=2012-07-01}}</ref> Pakistani blogger [[Ayaz Nizami]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://realisticapproach.org|title=جراتِ تحقیق - ہمتِ کفر ملے جراتِ تحقیق ملے|publisher=|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150829141838/http://realisticapproach.org/|archivedate=2015-08-29|df=}}</ref> the Vice President of the website and founder of realisticapproach.org, an Urdu website about atheism,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aaapakistan.org/|title=Atheist & Agnostic Alliance Pakistan|publisher=}}</ref> is currently detained under the charges of blasphemy and could face the death penalty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nation.com.pk/national/24-Mar-2017/blasphemy-crackdown-fia-arrests-2-suspects-from-karachi|title=Blasphemy crackdown: FIA arrests 2 suspects from Karachi|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/pakistani-christians-islam-lynching-trial-muslims-convert-youhanabad-lahore-church-bombings-a7659721.html|title=42 Christians told 'to convert to Islam or face death penalty'|date=31 March 2017|publisher=}}</ref> This happened shortly after that former Prime Minister of Pakistan [[Nawaz Sharif]] [[Internet censorship in Pakistan|supported a crackdown]] on blasphemous material posted on social media and described blasphemy as an "unpardonable offence" in March 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pakistan asks Facebook to help fight blasphemy|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-39300270|accessdate=19 April 2017|work=[[BBC]]|date=17 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Pakistani student accused of blasphemy beaten to death on campus|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pakistan-blasphemy-idUSKBN17F1ZL|accessdate=15 April 2017|work=Reuters|date=13 April 2017}}</ref>
